
[1]hazard

   HAZ'ARD, n. [L. casus, a fall, and ard, the common termination.]

   1. Chance; accident; casualty; a fortuitous event; that which falls or
   comes suddenly or unexpectedly, the cause of which is unknown, or whose
   operation is unforeseen or unexpected.

   I will stand the hazard of the die.

   2. Danger; peril; risk. He encountered the enemy at the hazard of his
   reputation and life.

   Men are led on from one stage of life to another, in a condition of the
   utmost hazard.

   3. A game at dice.

   To run the hazard, to risk; to take the chance; to do or neglect to do
    something, when the consequences are not foreseen, and not within the
                           powers of calculation.

   HAZ'ARD, v.t. To expose to chance; to put in danger of loss or injury;
   to venture; to risk; as, to hazard life to save a friend; to hazard an
       estate on the throw of a dice; to hazard salvation for temporal
                                  pleasure.

   Men hazard nothing by a course of evangelical obedience.

   1. To venture to incur, or bring on; as, to hazard the loss or
   reputation.

      HAZ'ARD, v.i. To try the chance; to adventure; to run the risk or
                                   danger.

   Pause a day or two, before you hazard--
